In this &#39;Hour of Code&#39; the CSE team from around APAC hope to teach you the basics of machine learning. Most importantly you learn that the most important part of doing good machine learning is being able to think about creative ways to use data… a gentle melding of artistry and pretty much just common sense… Having conversations about the creative use of data is something that we can all do with customers!

Before we do any modelling. Let&#39;s explore the data a little bit. Azure Machine Learning allows us to visualize the dataset with some simple charts to show the distribution of values.

1. **Click** n the small circled _1_ on the bottom of the module
2. **Click** on the _Visualize_ option
  1. **Find** the _HouseStyle_ feature and **Click** on that column

  3. **Explore** some other features. Which features do you think will be the best predictors of house price? How might we tell?

Note that this has _1459 Missing Values_. This is the unlabelled data that we need to make new predictions for.

We need to split the dataset into the training data (labelled) and the test data (unlabelled).
  1. **Wire** the bottom of the _ames.arff_ dataset to the top of the _Split Data_ module.

You will see little green &#39;s appear as the experiment is run.
5. **Visualize** the output datasets on the _Split Data_ module to check that we have correctly split out training and test data.

A very common approach to quickly checking the predictive power of each feature is to perform a correlation calculation. How does each feature correlate with our target variable of _SalePrice_.
We have a module in Azure Machine Learning which is able to help us to do this.

1. **Add** a _Filter Based Feature Selection_ module onto the canvas.
  1. **Wire** the module up to the left hand output of the split module
  2. In the _Properties_ editor **click** the _Launch column selector_ button
We need to tell the module which column we are using as our target
  3. **Find** the _SalePrice_ column at the bottom of the list and **Click** the _Arrow_ to add it to the selected columns.
2. **Run** the experiment
3. **Visualize** the right hand side output of the _Filter Based Feature Selection_ module
This is giving the correlation between each feature and _SalePrice._ How good was your intuition earlier on?
4. **Click** the _Save as_ button at the bottom of the page to save the Experiment using a name of your choice.

# Building a Basic Model

Now we&#39;ll build a basic model. We are going to be predicting the _SalePrice_ of the properties which is a continuous numeric variable. This process is called _Regression_ modelling. Azure ML offers a variety of models to perform regression. We will be using a model called a _Boosted Decision Tree_ model which has demonstrated itself as one of the best approaches to working with structured data like our housing dataset. You might like to try different modelling approaches later on.

1. **Drag** on a _Boosted Decision Tree Regression_ module
We&#39;ll just leave the properties of the model as the default at the moment.
2. **Drag** on a _Train Model_ module
3. **Wire** the _Boosted Decision Tree Regression_ module and our _training_ dataset to the _Train model_
Note how Azure ML helps you to make the correct choices when wiring up modules.
4. Use the _Column Selector_ to **select** the _SalePrice_ column
5. **Run** the experiment

We&#39;ve now built our first machine learning model! Well done. Let&#39;s visualize the model and we can see a little bit about how _decision tree_ modelling works; as well as being extremely powerful they&#39;re very understandable to the average lay-person. We&#39;ll skip the nitty-gritty of the &quot;boosting&quot; bit, but, if you&#39;d like to dive deep then chat with your mentor/instructor about it.

1. **Visualize** the output of _Train model_
You&#39;ll note that the model has built a whole bunch of what look like trees…albeit upside down!
2. **Explore** these trees by **zooming** in and out.
  1. Try **clicking** on one of the _leaf_ nodes (at the very bottom of the tree)
Note how the _Statistics_ shows the decision taken at each point in that path through the tree as well as the final prediction. Given that we only have a thousand or so rows of labelled data, the trees that we are building are probably more complex that we&#39;d like them to be. This will result in a phenomenon call _Over fitting_ and is something that you should probably consider when you try and optimize your model later.

# Scoring our Test data

Now that we have a model, let&#39;s use it to make predictions on test dataset.

1. **Drag** a _Score Model_ module onto the canvas
2. **Wire** it to the _Trained Model_
3. **Wire** to the _dataset2_ of the Split Dataset; remember, this is our testing data.
4. **Run** the model
5. **Visualize** the results.
If you scroll to the far right you&#39;ll see that the model has created a _Scored labels_ column. Because we are going to submit this to Kaggle for evaluation we need to remove unnecessary columns and to rename the _Scored labels_ column to _SalePrice._
6. **Add** a _Select Columns in Dataset_ module to the canvas
7. **Wire** this to the output of the _Score model_ module
8. Use the _Column selector_ to **select** the _Id_ and _Scored Labels_ columns
9. **Run** the experiment
10. **Add** an _Edit Metadata_ Module
11. Use the _Column selector_ to **select** the _Scored Labels_ column
12. **Set** the _New column names_ value to _SalePrice_
13. **Run** the Experiment
14. **Visualize** the last output
You should see a dataset containing _Id_ and _SalePrice_. This is the dataset that you&#39;ll be submitting at the end of the session.

# Validating our model

So, we&#39;ve now built and trained our model and then used that to make predictions on our un-labelled data. How good are those predictions? **The truth is, that we have no idea how good the predictions actually are.** We&#39;ve made predictions on our unlabelled data, but, in order to determine our prediction quality we really need to try making some predictions against data for which we know the correct value, i.e. our labelled data. This is a process called _Validation_. A common approach for validation is to take the labelled dataset, split it to say 80/20, and then use the 20% of the data to validate the model. Because we have such a small dataset we&#39;re going to use an approach called _Cross validation._ This will train the model multiple times, each time splitting out a different set of data to hold back. We can then use the quality of each of those models, as well as the variance in quality, to decide if we have a good model.

1. **Drag** out a _Cross Validate Model_ module
2. **Wire** this to the _Boosted Decision Tree Regression_ model
3. **Wire** to the _training_ dataset
4. Select **SalePrice** using the _Column Selector_
5. **Run** the model.
The _cross validation_ process can take some time; remember that it is running 10 models.
As datasets get larger, cross validation (and the hyper-parameter optimization we discuss below) become so time consuming that we will often run them across clusters of many servers in order to improve performance and reduce delay.
  1. You may also like to try **right clicking** on the module and choosing _Run selected_ as this will only run the modules required to perform the cross validation.
6. **Visualize** the _evaluation results by fold_ output.

You will see various evaluation measures for the quality of each of the 10 models on each of the 10 corresponding hold-out datasets. We won&#39;t go into too much detail on these; the easiest one to grasp intuitively is the _Coefficient of Determination_; This is basically a number from 0 to 100 that describes the proportion of variance in the _SalePrice_ that is explained by our model. When you start to try and improve your model below, it&#39;s a pretty good option to use for a quick check of model quality.

# Improving your Model with Feature Engineering

Now you&#39;ve built a full modelling experiment. We can now work to improve the quality of our model. Some things that we might try;

- Tune the _hyper-parameters_ of the model.
If you click on the _Boosted Decision Tree Model_ you&#39;ll see a range of settings that we can change. These can be tuned to improve the model.
- Perform _feature engineering_
One of the more artful parts of the data science process is performing feature engineering. We can take a ere we use our statistical knowledge, domain expertise and, in many cases, a good dollop of common sense to create new features based on existing data

Below we&#39;ve included some ideas to improve the overall performance of your model and, while we haven&#39;t provided detailed instructions, the instructor will run through these. Don&#39;t feel limited to these approaches; you now have a good model evaluation mechanism and so you are free to experiment.
It&#39;s worth writing down your performance each time you test the model (Average and StdDev of Coefficient of Determination)

You may want to skim the documentation for the dataset to get some ideas the you could use. [http://ww2.amstat.org/publications/jse/v19n3/decock.pdf](http://ww2.amstat.org/publications/jse/v19n3/decock.pdf) [https://ww2.amstat.org/publications/jse/v19n3/decock/datadocumentation.txt](https://ww2.amstat.org/publications/jse/v19n3/decock/datadocumentation.txt)

1. Use the _Hyper Parameter Optimization_ module.
  1. You can wire the _Trained Best Model_ from the _Tune Model Hyperparameters_ module directly to your _Score Model_ module.
  2. Take a look at the _Sweep Results_ and Visualize the best model. See how it differs from the model you trained earlier. Think about why the tuned model might be better in the context of _overfitting_.
2. Create some features using the _Execute R Script_ module.
The R Code below creates a feature that is mentioned in the Amstat journal paper. Specifically, the total of _Total Bsmt SqFt + Gr Liv Area_. Experiment with your own ideas based on what you think might influence price. You should create your features just above the data split so that they are created correctly for both Training and Testing data. When you create features you can try running (Use _Run selected_!) the _Filter Based Feature Selection_ module again for a quick check of expected performance.

# Map 1 - based optional input ports to variables
```r
dataset1 <- maml.mapInputPort(1) # class: data.frame
```

#Create a new column that adds
```r
dataset1$SumOfArea <- dataset1$TotalBsmtSF + dataset1$GrLivArea
```

# Sample operation
```r
data.set <- dataset1;
```

# Select data.frame to be sent to the output Dataset port
```r
maml.mapOutputPort('data.set');
```
